The paper deals with algorithmic problems on graphs, specifically those of bounded maximum induced matching width (mim-width). This suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of data structures (cs.DS) or computational geometry (cs.CG), as these fields often deal with graph algorithms. Additionally, the paper mentions specific graph classes such as interval graphs and convex graphs, which are often studied in the context of graph theory (cs.DM). The paper also uses techniques from graph theory and combinatorics (cs.GT) to develop its algorithms. Finally, the paper's focus on polynomial-time algorithms suggests that it could belong to the category of computational complexity (cs.CC).
